      </div>

      <h2 id="best-budget">Best Budget: Knitted Corduroy Desk Pad</h2>
      <p>If you prefer a fabric feel and want to spend under $12, the corduroy desk pad is a surprising value. The ribbed texture gives a distinctive look that hides wear better than flat cloth, and the padding is slightly thicker than the leather pad at roughly 4mm, which some users prefer for wrist comfort. Mouse tracking performance is comparable to the leather pad on speed and control based on material specifications.</p>
      <p>The tradeoff is spill resistance — there is none. The fabric absorbs liquid immediately, and spills may leave faint stains even after prompt blotting. The pad also picks up lint and crumbs more visibly than the leather alternative, requiring more frequent cleaning. For users who never eat or drink at their desk, the corduroy is a comfortable and attractive budget choice. For anyone who has ever spilled coffee, the leather pad is worth the small premium.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying Guide</h2>
      <p>Start by measuring your desk and your setup width. Lay your keyboard and mouse in their normal positions and measure the total width plus three inches of margin on each side. That is your minimum pad width. A pad that is too small creates dead zones where your mouse drops off the edge, and a pad that is too large hangs over the desk edge and collects dust underneath. The 36-inch length fits most full-size keyboard setups; if you use a tenkeyless or 75% board, a 31-inch pad will save money and desk space.</p>
      <p>Material choice comes down to how you use your desk. PU leather is the practical choice for most office workers because it is waterproof, easy to clean, and looks professional on video calls. Cloth pads offer better mouse control for gaming and design work but stain permanently and require more maintenance. If you do color-sensitive work, choose a neutral gray or black pad — patterned and colored pads can subtly affect how you perceive colors on screen due to ambient reflection.</p>
      <p>Finally, check the thickness and backing. Anything under 2mm will not provide meaningful wrist cushioning and will show desk imperfections through the surface. Anything over 5mm can destabilize keyboards with short feet and feel spongy under a heavy mouse hand. The 3-4mm range is the sweet spot. For the backing, look for textured suede or rubber — smooth backings slide around on glossy desk surfaces and you will be repositioning the pad daily.</p>
      <p>Learn more about our <a href="/how-we-test/">evaluation methodology</a> and <a href="/editorial-policy/">editorial policy</a>.</p>

      <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        <details>
          <summary>Is a leather desk pad better than a cloth mouse pad?</summary>
          <p>It depends on your mouse sensor and preference. Leather works with modern optical mice but can be slightly slower for gaming-grade tracking. Cloth offers more control and speed tuning. For office work, leather wins on spill resistance, durability, and unified desk aesthetics.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>What size desk pad do I need for a full setup?</summary>
          <p>Measure the width of your keyboard plus the mouse area you want covered. A 36 x 17 inch pad fits a full-size keyboard with dedicated mouse space on the right. If you use a tenkeyless or 75% board, 31 x 15 inches is sufficient. Always leave 2-3 inches of margin so the pad is not edge-to-edge.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Do waterproof desk pads actually repel coffee spills?</summary>
          <p>Genuine PU leather pads repel water-based spills including coffee, beading liquid so you can wipe it off. Real animal leather absorbs liquids unless treated. Cloth pads soak spills immediately and stain. Wipe any spill within a minute to prevent seeping into stitched edges.</p>
        </details>
      </div>

